EXPLANATION – Matter in bolded italics is new; matter between brackets [omitted material] is material to be omitted.
AN ACT relating to Medicaid; prohibiting the State Government
from the recovery of Medicaid benefits from an account
established under the Nevada ABLE Savings Program in
certain circumstances; and providing other matters
properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing federal law allows for the creation of a tax-advantaged savings account
2 for a person who has certain qualifying disabilities, which is commonly known as
3 an ABLE Account. Under the program, any person may make a contribution to the
4 ABLE Account of a person with a qualified disability. Any interest or other growth
5 in the value of the ABLE Account is not taxed, and any distribution from the ABLE
6 Account is not taxed if the distribution is used to pay expenses related to living a
7 life with a disability, including, without limitation, education, housing,
8 transportation, health care, employment training and support, and assistive
9 technology and personal support services. Money in an ABLE Account or
10 distributions from an ABLE Account do not affect the eligibility of a person for
11 certain public benefits such as Social Security disability payments, Supplemental
12 Nutrition Assistance Program benefits and Medicaid. To qualify for these
13 advantages of an ABLE Account, the savings account into which contributions are
14 made on behalf of a qualified person must be established and maintained by the
15 qualified person’s state of residence or another state that has adopted a qualified
16 program and entered into a contract with the qualified person’s state of residence.
17 (26 U.S.C. § 529A) Existing state law requires the State Treasurer, in cooperation
18 with the Aging and Disability Services Division of the Department of Health and
19 Human Services, to establish or otherwise ensure the establishment of the Nevada
